            "answer_text": "In early medieval times there were very intensive contacts between Nordmen (if you mean Scandinavians) and Slavs. Have in mind that in Northern Germany there were Slavic states directly neighbouring with Denmark. Scandinavian Vikings had outposts not only in Russia but also in Northern Poland. Viking mercenaries were used by early Polish leaders and actually they fought against other Scandinavians serving in Rus. When it comes to merging many Scandinavians settled in Slavic lands but there was also opposite process. Archeology shows signs of Slavic settlement in Denmark and also Sweden. In XII century Baltic Sea was arena of naval wars between Slavic and Scandinavian states (mostly Denmark) - settlement and getting slaves by both sides also happened. ",
